<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900918-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900918-0037.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>09/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GM AND THE UAW AGREED on a three-year contract. The termscall for the automaker to spend as much as $4 billion tosweeten a range of job and income security programs. Theagreement imposes restrictions on GM's ability to closeplants but apparently doesn't require the company to findwork for some 30,000 GM union members laid off during thepast three years.   ---</LP><TEXT>   A United Airlines union group seeking to buy United'sparent, UAL, plans to meet with banks this week about a newoffer of $175 to $180 a share, or $3.82 billion to $3.92billion, said people familiar with the deal.   ---   The G-7 nations' finance ministers and central bankerswill meet in Washington Saturday to discuss higher oilprices, recent interest rate rises, and the decline in thedollar.   ---   Charles Keating is to be arraigned today on criminal fraudcharges in a California state court. The charges are said toinclude allegations of fraudulent sales of debentures throughthe now-collapsed Lincoln Sandamp;L.   ---   Crude oil prices soared to records on the New YorkMercantile Exchange following events that pointed up thelikelihood of a war in the Middle East and possible supplydisrup tions. The October crude contract ended $1.87 a barrelhigher at $33.63.   ---   Budget negotiators continued to haggle over what price theDemocrats would demand for a cut in the capital-gains tax,and Bush renewed his call for such a reduction.   ---   Colonial Realty is the target of efforts by six banks toforce the company into involuntary bankruptcy-courtliquidation. Colonial's financial distress raises thepossibility of losses to the many individual investors in itsreal-estate partnerships.   ---   U.S. bankers are concerned that economic weakness willlead to increased defaults on credit-card debt.   ---   Italy's Pirelli proposed to West Germany's Continentalthat they merge their tire businesses to challenge France'sMichelin, America's Goodyear and Japan's Bridgestone.   ---   U.S. bank regulators would be allowed to raise depositinsurance premiums to whatever levels they feel necessaryunder a bill passed by the House. Separately, bank regulatorssettled a dispute over capital levels.   ---   NCR is expected to unveil today a redesign of its productline based on Intel's computer chips and software.   ---   Sears debt was downgraded by Moody's, which loweredratings on about $6.9 billion of the company's securities.The ratings agency said a continuing drop in consumer spending will hamper the company's efforts to boost merchandisingresults.   ---   The Japanese stock market is the focus of new futures andoptions offered by three major U.S. exchanges.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 110,600,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2567.33, up 3.22; transportation 887.94, off 1.48; utilities199.89, up 0.69.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3329.12,off 9.80.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.74, up 0.45; spotindex 129.35, up 0.28.   Dollar: 136.55 yen, off 0.40; 1.5480 marks, off 0.023.</TEXT></DOC>